## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to design pluggable, runtime-extendable components with clean isolation between tenants and core logic. It exercises registry design, immutable pipelines, and safe runtime extension.

## Key Concepts
- Chain of Responsibility
- Registry + factory pattern
- Runtime extensibility with per-tenant manifests
- Immutability and thread-safety in pipelines

## Code Example
```javascript
class ILogProcessor {
  async process(entry, next) { throw new Error('not implemented') }
}

class ProcessorRegistry {
  constructor(){ this.factories = new Map() }
  register(name, factory){ this.factories.set(name, factory) }
  buildPipeline(names){
    let next = async () => {}
    for (let i = names.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
      const F = this.factories.get(names[i])
      const proc = new F()
      const prev = next
      next = async () => { await proc.process(null, prev) }
    }
    return next
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle processor ordering changes at runtime while preserving ongoing log streams?
- How would you test pipelines for tenant isolation and regressions when new processors are added?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a pluggable validation system that can be extended without touching core logic, a common real-world requirement in ingestion pipelines.

## Key Concepts

- Registry/Factory pattern for runtime extensibility
- Pipeline that composes validators by config
- Early exit on first failure for efficient feedback

## Code Example

```javascript
// Minimal interface and registry
class Validator {
  validate(record) { return { ok: true }; }
}
class EmailValidator extends Validator {
  validate(record) {
    const ok = /^[^@]+@[^@]+\.[^@]+$/.test(record.email || '');
    return ok ? { ok: true } : { ok: false, error: 'Invalid email' };
  }
}
const Registry = new Map();
function register(name, factory) { Registry.set(name, factory); }
function createValidator(name) { const f = Registry.get(name); return f ? f() : null; }

class ValidationPipeline {
  constructor(registry, keys) {
    this.registry = registry;
    this.keys = keys;
  }
  validate(record) {
    for (const k of this.keys) {
      const v = this.registry.get(k) ? this.registry.get(k)() : null;
      if (!v) continue;
      const res = v.validate(record);
      if (!res.ok) return res;
    }
    return { ok: true };
  }
}

// Usage
register('Email', () => new EmailValidator());
register('NonEmpty', () => new Validator());
const keys = ['Email'];
const pipeline = new ValidationPipeline(Registry, keys);
const result = pipeline.validate({ email: 'a@b.com' });
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you handle async validators?
- How would you test the registry and pipeline separately?
- How would you version validators and roll back if a validator changes semantics?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design runtime-extensible backends using patterns beyond a single factory, with practical concerns like data transfer and policy-based selection.

## Key Concepts
- **Strategy**: Choose a backend at runtime based on plan characteristics
- **Registry**: Register backends by name and instantiate lazily
- **Abstraction**: Small Backend interface minimizes ground-truth coupling
- **Safety**: Backends declare capability and isolation

## Code Example
```javascript
interface Plan { /* ... */ }
interface ExecContext { /* ... */ }
interface ExecutionResult { rows: any[]; metadata?: Record<string, unknown>; }

interface Backend {
  supports(plan: Plan): boolean;
  execute(plan: Plan, ctx: ExecContext): Promise<ExecutionResult>;
}

type BackendFactory = () => Backend;

class BackendRegistry {
  private factories = new Map<string, BackendFactory>();
  private instances = new Map<string, Backend>();

  register(name: string, factory: BackendFactory): void {
    this.factories.set(name, factory);
  }

  get(name: string): Backend | null {
    if (!this.instances.has(name)) {
      const factory = this.factories.get(name);
      if (!factory) return null;
      this.instances.set(name, factory());
    }
    return this.instances.get(name)!;
  }

  listAvailable(): string[] {
    return Array.from(this.factories.keys());
  }
}

class QueryPlanner {
  constructor(private registry: BackendRegistry) {}

  private selectBackend(plan: Plan): Backend | null {
    const available = this.registry.listAvailable();

    // Policy: prefer GPU for vectorizable plans, fallback to CPU
    if (available.includes('gpu')) {
      const gpu = this.registry.get('gpu');
      if (gpu?.supports(plan)) return gpu;
    }

    if (available.includes('fpga')) {
      const fpga = this.registry.get('fpga');
      if (fpga?.supports(plan)) return fpga;
    }

    // Default fallback
    if (available.includes('cpu')) {
      return this.registry.get('cpu');
    }

    return null;
  }

  async execute(plan: Plan, ctx: ExecContext): Promise<ExecutionResult> {
    const backend = this.selectBackend(plan);
    if (!backend) throw new Error('No suitable backend found');
    return backend.execute(plan, ctx);
  }
}

// Usage example
const registry = new BackendRegistry();

// Register backends at runtime
registry.register('cpu', () => new CPUBackend());
registry.register('gpu', () => new GPUBackend());
registry.register('fpga', () => new FPGABackend());

const planner = new QueryPlanner(registry);

const plan: Plan = { type: 'vector_scan', data: [1,2,3,4] };
const ctx: ExecContext = { sessionId: 'abc123' };

// Planner picks optimal backend based on policy
const result = await planner.execute(plan, ctx);
```

