## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to apply the Strategy pattern for runtime configurability, plus a registry to add new policies without touching cache internals.

## Key Concepts

- Strategy pattern
- Registry
- Runtime configurability
- Testability

## Code Example

```javascript
interface CachePolicy {
  onHit(key: string, value: any): void;
  evict(cache: Map<string, any>, capacity: number): string | null;
}
class Cache {
  private policy: CachePolicy;
  constructor(private store: Map<string, any>, registry: PolicyRegistry) {
    this.policy = registry.get('LRU');
  }
  access(key: string, value?: any) {
    if (value !== undefined) this.store.set(key, value);
    this.policy.onHit(key, this.store);
    if (this.store.size > 100) {
      const evicted = this.policy.evict(this.store, 100);
      if (evicted) this.store.delete(evicted);
    }
  }
}
class PolicyRegistry {
  private factories: Map<string, () => CachePolicy> = new Map();
  register(name: string, f: () => CachePolicy) { this.factories.set(name, f); }
  get(name: string): CachePolicy { return this.factories.get(name)!(); }
}
```

